    {
      "id": "dbaa60283d66e6a773393216692b4ff37342f7b6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-03-08 01:53:44.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nDi, I don't understand your reasoning about not consuming another bit for MDT, yet consuming a bit for LU_SEQ_RANGE_ALL (which has no real meaning).\n\nThe reason we picked LU_SEQ_RANGE_MDT == 0 was for backward compatibility, but if we need to add a bit to handle the distinction between MDT and OST, then I'd rather use that bit to positively identify MDT ranges.\n\nThat said, why does the FLD query need to specify the type at all?  Couldn't the query just return the sequence range, and then the caller decides whether it wants that type of FID?  That will make more sense when we have unified targets and the client doesn't really care what the type is.  Also, there should never be overlapping FID ranges for both OST and MDT types.\n\nI don't really consider this flag to be part of the query, only the SEQ should be the key, and the type is just information that is returned for the specific range.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "82abd405a9d897634bc34d32b982c0ab4294d8dc",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-03-08 20:20:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nHmm, in current implementation, it validates lsr_flags on the server side, which was added when we added this lsr_flags. (2.1), if we stop setting lsr_flags in the query request, I am afraid the new client will not work with old server.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
